In other words, the observed outcomes are the potential outcomes corresponding to the assigned treatment, which also known as the consistency assumption in the causal literature. We assume that the stable unit treatment value assumption (STUVA) holds, i.e., there should not be alternative forms of the treatment (i.e., incentives) and interference between units. In addition, we follow previous studies to assume that the unconfoundedness assumption holds, i.e., (ğ¶ğ‘¢,ğ‘– (0), ğ¶ğ‘¢,ğ‘– (1), ğ‘Œğ‘¢,ğ‘– (0), ğ‘Œğ‘¢,ğ‘– (1)) âŠ¥âŠ¥ ğ‘‡ğ‘¢,ğ‘– |ğ‘‹ğ‘¢,ğ‘– and let ğœ‚ < P(ğ‘‡ğ‘¢,ğ‘– = 1|ğ‘‹ğ‘¢,ğ‘– = ğ‘¥) < 1âˆ’ğœ‚, where âŠ¥âŠ¥ means independent and ğœ‚ is a constant between 0 and 1/2. In the personalized incentive scenarios, the rationality of the unconfoundedness assumption is due to the fact that the recommendation system gives incentives only based on the observed user and item features. When no incentives are released, it is obvious that users cannot actively collect incentives, i.e., ğ¶ğ‘¢,ğ‘– (0) = 0. Next, we assume that incentive collection ğ¶ğ‘¢,ğ‘– has a non-negative effect on conversion ğ‘Œğ‘¢,ğ‘– , i.e., there is no individual with (ğ¶ğ‘¢,ğ‘– (0) = 0, ğ¶ğ‘¢,ğ‘– (1) = 1, ğ‘Œğ‘¢,ğ‘– (0) = 1, ğ‘Œğ‘¢,ğ‘– (1) = 0), who does not convert when the incentive is actively collected, but converts when there is no incentive. In addition, because of the limitations of the collected information, some unmeasured confounders (e.g., userâ€™s income, etc.) may also affect coupon collecting and item purchasing, which poses additional challenges. In Figure 1, we summarize the causal diagram of Coupon Releasingâ†’Coupon Collectingâ†’Item Purchasing in e-commerce.
From a counterfactual perspective, as shown in Table 1, we divide all user-item pairs into five strata based on the joint potential outcomes (ğ¶ (0), ğ¶ (1), ğ‘Œ (0), ğ‘Œ (1)) of individuals, and named as "never buyer", "never taker", "coupon taker", "coupon buyer", and " always buyer", respectively. For simplification, we denote the labels of the five groups as ğ‘Œ0000, ğ‘Œ0011, ğ‘Œ0100, ğ‘Œ0101, and ğ‘Œ0111, correspondingly. Previous studies have modeled the conditional average treatment effect (CATE, also known as uplift modeling) to determine which users should be given incentives. Formally, CATE is defined as
ğœ (ğ‘¥ğ‘¢,ğ‘– ) = E(ğ‘Œ (1) âˆ’ ğ‘Œ (0) | ğ‘‹ = ğ‘¥ğ‘¢,ğ‘– ) = E(ğ‘Œ0101 | ğ‘‹ = ğ‘¥ğ‘¢,ğ‘– ),
which is equivalent to the probability that a unit with feature ğ‘¥ğ‘¢,ğ‘– belongs to "Coupon Buyer".
